>cnihta</i>) + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. This is the usual spelling of the name in Ireland, where it has been establishes since the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":11,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":21,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":31,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray",